  <h1>Mangalore – The Coastal Gem of Karnataka</h1>
  <p>Situated along the Arabian Sea, Mangalore (officially Mangaluru) is a vibrant port city known for its rich history, diverse culture, pristine beaches, and delicious cuisine. Often referred to as the “Gateway to Karnataka’s Coast,” Mangalore offers a perfect blend of tradition, modernity, and natural beauty.</p>

  <h1>Historical & Cultural Heritage</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Mangalore’s history dates back to ancient times as an important trading port connecting to the Middle East and Europe.</li>
    <li>The city is home to diverse communities including Tuluvas, Konkanis, Bearys, and Muslims, contributing to its multicultural fabric.</li>
    <li>Architectural landmarks include the 16th-century St. Aloysius Chapel, Kadri Manjunath Temple, and Sultan Battery fort.</li>
    <li>Mangalore is famous for its traditional Yakshagana dance-drama and vibrant festivals like Dasara and Mardi.</li>
  </ul>

  <h1>Top Attractions & Natural Beauty</h1>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Panambur Beach:</strong> A clean and lively beach known for its sunsets, beach festivals, and water sports.</li>
    <li><strong>Someshwara Beach:</strong> Known for rocky shores and the ancient Someshwara Temple nearby.</li>
    <li><strong>St. Aloysius Chapel:</strong> Renowned for its beautiful frescoes and impressive architecture.</li>
    <li><strong>Kukke Subramanya Temple:</strong> A famous pilgrimage site near Mangalore, dedicated to Lord Subramanya.</li>
    <li><strong>Mangaladevi Temple:</strong> The city’s namesake temple, dedicated to Goddess Mangaladevi.</li>
    <li><strong>Ullal Beach and Lighthouse:</strong> A quieter beach spot with scenic views and historical significance.</li>
    <li><strong>Pilgrimage Spots:</strong> Including the famous Dharmasthala and Kateel temples located within reachable distances.</li>
  </ul>

